    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 using the full series (do NOT filter by incident window). Then filter metric points to the incident window 2024-01-20 16:25:45 to 2024-01-20 16:55:45 UTC and detect anomaly points where value >= global P95. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) produce a compact aggregate with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC, ISO format), max_value_in_window. Sort results by anomaly_count desc and return at most top 20 rows. Also return a small summary listing unique cmdb_id values that have at least one anomaly and the number of distinct anomalous KPIs per such component (limit to top 20). Do not print full raw timeseries; keep outputs compact." }

{
    "analysis": "The metric analysis step identified many anomalous \"socket\" KPIs across multiple services during the incident window. Examples: catalogue.socket, catalogue-db.socket, orders-db.socket, queue-master.socket, rabbitmq.socket, session-db.socket, payment.socket, user.socket, user-db.socket, and carts-db.socket all show anomaly_count equal to most or all points in the incident window (many with anomaly_count=25). This pattern indicates widespread elevated socket measurements during the window, consistent with a network/socket level problem rather than an isolated CPU/memory spike. Multiple services show several distinct anomalous KPIs too (components such as payment, catalogue, carts, orders, user each have multiple anomalous KPI types). To localize the root cause we must (1) confirm if logs/error messages indicate socket/network errors, and (2) check traces to determine the most downstream faulty service if multiple service-level faults appear in the same traces. At this point we are not finished: we need compact log and trace evidence to pick the root-cause component and reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv and error_logs.csv and filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-20 16:25:45 to 2024-01-20 16:55:45 UTC. Produce compact aggregates only: (A) From log.csv group by cmdb_id and log_name and return for each group: cmdb_id, log_name, count (points in window), max_value_in_window, earliest_timestamp_where_value>0 (ISO UTC) — limit to top 50 groups sorted by count desc. (B) From error_logs.csv group by cmdb_id and message and return for each group: cmdb_id, message (truncated to first 200 chars), count, earliest_timestamp (ISO UTC) — limit to top 50 rows sorted by count desc. If there are no rows for either file in the window, return an explicit empty indicator for that file. Keep outputs compact (no raw full log prints), and store full filtered tables in kernel variables for follow-up." }

{
    "analysis": "From the metric analysis we found a strong, system-wide signal: many services show consecutive anomalies on their \"socket\" KPIs during the incident window (catalogue.socket, catalogue-db.socket, orders-db.socket, queue-master.socket, rabbitmq.socket, session-db.socket, payment.socket, user.socket, user-db.socket, carts-db.socket, etc.). Several components have multiple distinct anomalous KPIs as well. This pattern is consistent with a network/socket-level problem rather than an isolated CPU, memory, or disk issue. Log inspection found no error log entries in error_logs.csv during the window and log.error_count values are zero in many services; log.row_count shows normal/instrumentation counts but not error details. Given multiple service-level faulty components, we need trace analysis to localize which faulty service is the most downstream faulty service in call chains (the root-cause service) and confirm whether traces show increased latency/failures. Therefore we must analyze trace.csv by computing global thresholds per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full trace series, then detect anomalies inside the incident window and identify which services show trace anomalies and their earliest anomaly times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv and (1) compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full available series (do NOT filter by incident window). (2) Filter trace points to the incident window 2024-01-20 16:25:45 to 2024-01-20 16:55:45 UTC. (3) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) detect anomaly points where value >= global_p95. Produce a compact aggregate table with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (ISO UTC), max_value_in_window. Sort by anomaly_count desc and return at most top 20 rows. Also return a short list of unique cmdb_id values that have at least one trace anomaly and the number of distinct anomalous trace_names per such component (limit top 20). Store full filtered trace rows in a kernel variable for follow-up but do not print full raw traces." }

{
    "analysis": "Metric analysis (global P95 thresholds computed over full series) found a strong, concurrent pattern of anomalies on \"socket\" KPIs across many services during the incident window (catalogue.socket, catalogue-db.socket, orders-db.socket, queue-master.socket, rabbitmq.socket, session-db.socket, payment.socket, user.socket, user-db.socket, carts-db.socket, etc.). Many of those socket series show anomaly_count == full-window sample count (25), i.e., they were elevated across the entire incident window. Log inspection showed no error entries in error_logs.csv for the window and log.error_count is often 0; log.row_count exists but does not indicate specific service errors. Trace analysis returned no trace anomalies (trace data in-window is empty), so we cannot disambiguate downstream services using traces. Among the candidate application services (carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user), the payment service has the highest number of distinct anomalous KPIs in the compact summary (7 distinct anomalous KPIs) and shows multiple socket-related anomalies as well as other anomalies, making it the strongest single-service candidate. The cross-service pattern of socket anomalies suggests a network/socket-level failure rather than CPU/memory/disk resource saturation. Given (1) widespread socket KPI anomalies, (2) absence of application error logs, (3) payment as the most-severely affected application service in the metric summary, the likely root cause is a socket/network failure affecting multiple services with the payment service being the most impacted service component. However, to finalize confidently we should retrieve compact, per-KPI anomaly details for the payment service within the incident window (earliest anomaly timestamp, counts, and severity vs global P95) to confirm timing and severity before declaring the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter metric.csv for cmdb_id == 'payment'. For each payment kpi_name compute the global P95 using the full series (do NOT filter by the incident window), then filter payment metric points to the incident window 2024-01-20 16:25:45 to 2024-01-20 16:55:45 UTC and detect anomaly points where value >= global_p95. Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) with columns: kpi_name, global_p95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (ISO UTC), max_value_in_window. Sort by anomaly_count desc. Store full filtered payment rows in a kernel variable but do not print full raw time series." }

